ce:section.ce:para:
The analysis of the Mean Square Displacement (MSD) for Li+, Na+, and K+ ions in the H2TiO3 (Fig. 15
                        ) structure reveals significant variations in their diffusion behavior, offering valuable insights into the ion transport mechanisms within the material (Revil and Jougnot, 2008). Over the 500 ps simulation period, each ion exhibits a distinct MSD evolution, reflecting their unique interactions with the H2TiO3 matrix (As shown in Fig. 15). Li+ ions demonstrate the highest diffusivity, with an MSD curve that is steep and nearly linear, reaching a value of approximately 0.38 Å2 at 500 ps. The steady upward trend in the Li+ MSD curve, with no sign of saturation, indicates continuous, unimpeded diffusion throughout the simulation. According to the calculated diffusion coefficient (Table 7
                        ), for Li+ (D(Li+) = 9.5513 × 10−5 Å2/ps) and the high correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.8556) further support a well-defined, rapid transport mechanism within the H2TiO3 lattice. In contrast, Na+ ions exhibit more moderate diffusivity, with a calculated diffusion coefficient of D(Na+) = 1.1888 × 10−5 Å2/ps. The Na+ MSD curve shows a gradual increase, reaching approximately 0.08 Å2 at 500 ps, but its slope is less pronounced compared to Li+, reflecting a slower, yet steady diffusion process. The lower R2 value (0.8113) indicates some deviations from ideal linear diffusion, potentially due to intermittent barriers or trapping events encountered by Na+ ions along their diffusion pathway. K+ ions, however, display the most restricted mobility. With a diffusion coefficient of D(K+) = 6.5958 × 10−6 Å2/ps, the MSD curve for K+ is nearly flat, with a slight increase to around 0.075 Å2 at 370 ps, followed by a subtle decline. This behaviour, along with the very low R2 value (0.1742), suggests a complex and non-linear diffusion process, likely involving significant trapping or blocking events within the structure, preventing long-range diffusion. The pronounced selectivity of H2TiO3 for Li+ over Na+ and K+ can be attributed to several factors related to the physical properties of the ions and their interaction with the material. Li+, with its smaller ionic radius (0.76 Å), is better able to navigate through the interstitial spaces of the H2TiO3 lattice compared to Na+ (1.02 Å) and K+ (1.38 Å). Additionally, higher charge density of Li+, due to its smaller size, likely facilitates stronger, more dynamic interactions with the anionic framework of H2TiO3. These interactions may promote a hopping diffusion mechanism, enabling faster transport between adjacent sites. The structural characteristics of H2TiO3 also play a critical role in this selective diffusion. The material likely contains pathways or channels that are geometrically optimized for Li+ transport, creating an energetically favorable landscape for its diffusion. In contrast, the poor fit of K+ diffusion data to a linear model (R2 = 0.1742), coupled with the observed MSD trend, suggests that K+ ions encounter substantial diffusion barriers. These barriers may include trapping or blocking effects, further highlighting the material's preference for smaller, more mobile ions such as Li+ (Muy et al., 2021).
